My cup is overflowing - כּוֹסִי רְוָיָֽה - after reuniting with the @adamahfarm community this weekend.
•
In 2016, I left my job at an investment bank and did Adamah- a three month Jewish farming fellowship. It was there that I fell in love with the ancient cycle of composting, there that I watched @storyofstuff, which made me question assumptions I didn’t even know I had (“this is water”), and there that I did a lot of reflecting on the life I want to live. 
•
If you’d like to explore Judaism (especially earth-based Judaism), regenerative agriculture, and intentional community the Adamah Fellowship might be a good fit for you.

Join us at Materials for the Arts on Monday, January 9 at 5:00pm for a LIVE show recording of the podcast Person Place Thing with Randy Cohen featuring waste expert and activist Anna Sacks (@thetrashwalker). Dedicated to passing waste legislation in NYC and raising awareness about consumption, Anna Sacks shares her trash diving adventures with nearly half a million followers across TikTok, Instagram, and Twitter as "The Trash Walker." Sacks also serves as the Legislative Chair of the Manhattan Solid Waste Advisory Board and is co-founder of the #SaveOurCompost coalition.

MFTA invites you to our warehouse for this special Person Place Thing show recording, featuring music from fiddle player Reid Jenkins. Enjoy refreshments and conversations with NYC’s creative community.

The media needs to do a better job reporting on incinerators.
•
It is an incinerator. It is not a renewable energy facility. It is not a recycling plant. It is an incinerator, where we burn material deemed trash.
•
Even calling incineration “waste-to-energy” is misleading. Landfills with energy capture can also technically be called waste-to-energy, but they’re first and foremost landfills. 
•
Journalists, please be straightforward - call it an incinerator. Avoid greenwashing for the incineration industry and avoid confusing people

Personally, not a fan of this change!
•
1. Framing 8pm set out for trash as a rat mitigation effort is based on no evidence. Rats are nocturnal

2. Based on testimony heard at hearing, this will negatively impact building staff who are tasked with putting out waste. They'll have to travel and arrive home later

This will also negatively impact Canners (people who make living collecting and redeeming cans). They'll need to start and end work later and do more work in the dark

3. This will reduce our informal reuse economy. Currently with 4 pm set out time, people see bulky items on the curb, send to curb alert accounts like @stoopingnyc @scoopthestoopnyc and then have time to figure out how to transport home. With setout of 8 pm, there will be fewer eyes to spot bulky furniture to begin with and less time to bring it home.

This will just result in more material being sent to landfills and incinerators, which has major environmental and financial implications (NYC already spends $460 million per year transporting "trash" to them).

At the very least, there should be a carve out for furniture or bulky items so there’s a greater likelihood they’ll be rehomed instead of buried or burned.

4. There is no grace period - meaning buildings willl start getting fined right away for noncompliance. This is unusual for such a major rule change. UPDATE: there is now a one month grace period (this is new)

5. I think public input wasn't sufficiently sought or heard. There was one public hearing (I testified) and the vast vast majority of people who spoke raised these concerns

Today was a major win for those who care about composting, soil health, greenhouse gas emissions, and zero waste to landfills and incinerators.
•
NYC City Council passed the most transformative change to residential waste since 1989, when curbside recycling was established.
•
Now, at last, organics (food scraps and yard waste) must also be recycled either into compost or energy via anaerobic digestion.
•
If everyone complies, we could reduce the amount of waste we send to landfills and incinerators by 33% and we could save the city over $40 million per year.
•
It has taken years to get here! Thank you to the leadership of @cmsandynurse, @shahanafrombk, @ebottcher, Keith Powers, @galeabrewer, @nycspeakeradams, and many more (this was the most sponsored bill of this session!). 
•
We have more work to do - especially around increasing community composting and reducing food waste to begin with - but this is a major transformative win.

Please join us on Monday at 6 pm ET for a very important discussion around organics (food scraps & yard waste) processing in NYC! Link in bio to register (free & virtual).
•
Now that mandatory universal curbside collection of organics has passed, what will happen to the material collected and how will it be beneficially used?
•
We’ll provide an overview of organics in NYC (@cfzw_design) and then discuss current large scale solutions: community composting (@bigreuse), industrial composting (@compostingcouncil), and anaerobic digestion (@nycwater).
• 
We need the public to understand more about each process and then be involved in decision making as the city ramps up processing facilities in the years to come to accommodate increased collection.
•
We’re really lucky to have an expert group of panelists and moderation by @cmsandynurse. Hope you can join us!

Last month, creator Anna Sacks, aka @thetrashwalker, shared the above video of herself “dumpster diving” in the trash bags placed in front of a recently shut down Starbucks.

In the bag, she found various food items, including egg bites, croissants, Teavana Green iced tea, brownies, croissants, and bagels, Kind Bars, and biscotti, all in individually sealed wrappers.

“In this video, Starbucks can confirm that the food pictured was no longer deemed safe to transfer or donate per food donation standards, and per policy were required to discard,” a Starbucks spokesperson told Green Matters exclusively via email.

Even if one is to give Starbucks the benefit of the doubt and assume the above statement is true, the company’s excuse does not apply to the inedible items Sacks found in Starbucks’ trash. In the video, she uncovered items like unused Starbucks paper cups, plastic cups, stirrers, gift cards, and a “million” napkins.

“There clearly was no safety issue with these items,” Sacks tells Green Matters exclusively. “Instead, in my opinion, it was an issue of lack of store closing protocol.”

“Instead of tossing usable items, Starbucks could transfer the supplies to another nearby store,” Sacks tells us, adding that there is an existing Starbucks two blocks away, and another one opening one block away.

Ending 2023 incredible grateful to be a part of NYC’s community composting community. @nycmayor and @nycsanitation Commissioner Tisch announced that they were eliminating all funding for community composting right before Thanksgiving. Since then, we have spent hours and hours and hours organizing to reverse these foolish and cruel budget cuts. @grownyc’s petition received over 45k signatures. @queensbotanicalgarden and others hosted group phone banking targeting our elected officials. @saveourcompost and @grownycworkers planned three rallies in one month with hundreds of people showing up to support community composting. We received press coverage. Private donors put in their own money to preserve some of the community composting jobs and infrastructure. And still it wasn’t enough.
•
Today, because of @nycmayor and @nycsanitation Commissioner Tisch’s ill thought through decisions, all public funding for community composting has been eliminated and dozens of New Yorkers who have devoted their careers to making NYC a more sustainable and healthy place are losing their jobs. By eliminating the Master Composter Program, all education and outreach for curbside food scraps collection, food scrap drop off sites at Green Markets, and local community composting sites, NYC’s annual budget of $100+ billion will be reduced by a whopping 0.006%, a literal rounding error.
•
I am incredibly disappointed in the leadership of Mayor Adams and Sanitation Commissioner Tisch. And I’m disheartened that, once again, environmental programs are among the first programs to be eliminated during a budget crisis, as if we are not in a simultaneous environmental crisis. 
•
There is a narrow possibility that in the coming days NYC Council could rejected the Mayor’s budget cuts. We’ll be urging the Speaker to do so.
•
Either way, we have more work to do in 2024. Namely: we need to pass a law in NYC City Council protecting community composting and we need to make sure funding is restored in the next fiscal budget.
•
Ending the year grateful to be in this community and thinking of all those who are losing their jobs today. We will continue to fight

Multiply this by the tens of thousands of retailers and corporations where this happens.
